@descent3me I'm not sure how much more detail I can give beyond the linked writeup (which is pretty much exactly what happened here). Let me know if something from there is unclear.

With respect to why the recursive includes in the manifest didn't work: a manifest is required for source distributions (`sdist`); `python setup.py sdist` uses it for what to include in the `tar.gz` artifact. But that artifact is not actually installable; when `pip` is pointed to a tar, [it still has to build the package](https://packaging.python.org/tutorials/distributing-packages/#source-distributions). That's where the package definition within `setup.py:setup(...)` comes in, and where we were incorrect. 

It should also be noted that a manifest is only used for created source distributions, not wheels (which is preferred by `pip`).

Hi guys, I've just meet the same issue as @agerrius and traced it down to `SGSpatialSort::FindPositions()`. There is a code at the very bottom of this method, that checks if smoothing group is zero and treats it as a smooth vertex/edge:

```c++
// if the given smoothing group is 0, we'll return all surrounding vertices
if (!pSG)
{
    ...
}
```

This gives you a smooth mesh if it misses a smooth groups information chunk in 3DS.  However, if you load such mesh in 3D Studio Max - you get all the edges hard:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/151412/26569590/9af64686-455f-11e7-8d25-2059e7c30919.png)

The solution seems to be to remove that check and treat zero smoothing group as "hard", but before submitting a patch I'd like to double-check if this is done intentionally. I see the same code is being used at ASE import, too, so maybe it needs to work a different way there?

