@abhi18av If you add `--cache-syllabus` option, course's syllabus will be saved to file `<course-name>-syllabus-parsed.json` in current directory. If you also add `--only-syllabus`, the script will stop after saving a syllabus to a file. If you run the script again with `--cache-syllabus`, it will read syllabus from the file instead of downloading it from Coursera again.

Using this two options you can preview materials that are available to download. In fact, you can adjust syllabus and remove unwanted materials. It may be not very convenient without good editor JSON support though.

There is a slight nuance. Certain materials are downloaded to memory during the parsing stage, for example quiz HTML texts and images.

