@neuromusic I agree that if you want fast query performance across large collections of files then we'll likely need some form of acceleration structure, whether it be a database index or some other form of query structure if only because the time to simply open files will kill performance. However, I would say that this is not really a problem of HDF5 but rather file-based solutions in general. Data exchange and query across files have very different requirements so it is not surprising that one storage solution may not serve all needs optimally.  In addition to "pure" alternative backends (e.g., all data be routed to a database), I think as we explore this space we'll likely find that we probably want some hybrid solutions, e.g., large binary data blocks stored in HDF5 and metadata and data statistics stored in a database for query. Designing these kind of systems is a large effort in itself. My feeling right now is that this probably something we want to explore but it may not be something we want NWB to "officially" standardize at this point.

@lfrank I think rather than a full solution, what you have suggest is to take a first step to help make the pure HDF5 solution work more efficiently with queries by separating data into 1) small HDF5 files with metadata and 2) large auxiliary HDF5 files that are linked to the metadata files. What this would accomplish is that you at least would only need to touch the smaller metadata files when querying data but still have an easy way to get to the raw data blocks. 

@ajtritt @neuromusic  @lfrank I think as part of this ticket we probably want to focus on the proposal that @lfrank has raised and have the discussion about alternative backends to accelerate queries in a separate thread. 

In terms of implementing the proposal, I think this really only affects the data write as the data read can already handle external links. As such, what would be needed are ways to write some parts of an NWBContainer to different locations. I could imagine different solution to accomplish this:

1) We could enhance the HDF/IO backend to allow us to write individual objects and provide a list of the fields it should write. Those fields could then be replaced by the corrsonding HDF5 datasets so that in the next write they would become external links. This would split the write into two main steps: 1) write the large data portions that should go to external files first and then 2) write the remaining data to a single metadata file.

2) We could design some ability to provide write hints for individual fields of an NWBContainer.

In general, the main complication I see is for attributes that are associated with an external data block. I'm not sure if we can seperate those attributes from the data block

